Bayesian modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

The purpose of this project to develop a Baysean regression model to predict the audience_score from given explanatory and new created variables. The final model is expected to be optimized to use a fewer set of explanatory variables thus making it simpler and predict the good/accurate value for audience score. Details of steps taken to arrive at this model is explained below in steps.

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)
library(BAS)
library(GGally)
library(MASS)

Load data

load("movies.gz")

Part 1: Data

The IMDb is an online information database of movies, TV programs and other titles, it also includes information of common interest like cast,summaries,etc. with data coming from various sources. The database also covers international titles. The sample database provided for this exercise filters out non-US movies and movies in the sample included are for the period 1970 onwards, whereas the IMDB database includes movie data since 1874 (approx 4.6million movies). The Rotten Tomatoes is a review aggregator site for film and TV.

Both databases contain observational data collected from various sources and due to their size and independent variety of sources could be categorized as random.

Generalization and Causability

The inferences from this exercise will have generalizability limited to the filters used in selecting the sample that is for US movies and limited to the period 1970-2016. The inferences will not be the basis of forming causal relationships due to lack of random assignment.

Part 2: Data manipulation

As required, the code below creates 5 new variables (feature_film, drama, summer_season,oscar_season & mpaa_rating_R) and initializes them from the sample movies data, populating them with ‘yes’ or ‘no’ based on conditions mentioned in the project exercise.

movies <- movies %>% mutate (feature_film = ifelse (title_type == 'Feature Film','yes','no'))
movies$feature_film <- as.factor(movies$feature_film) 


movies <- movies %>% mutate (drama = ifelse (genre == 'Drama','yes','no'))
movies$drama <- as.factor(movies$drama)


movies <- movies %>% mutate (summer_season = ifelse (thtr_rel_month %in% c(5,6,7,8),'yes','no'))
movies$summer_season <- as.factor(movies$summer_season)


movies <- movies %>% mutate (oscar_season = ifelse (thtr_rel_month %in% c(10,11,12),'yes','no'))
movies$oscar_season <- as.factor(movies$oscar_season)


movies <- movies %>% mutate (mpaa_rating_R = ifelse (mpaa_rating == 'R','yes','no'))
movies$mpaa_rating_R <- as.factor(movies$mpaa_rating_R)

Part 4: Modeling

We start by taking a first look at how audience_score depends on all other variables (full model) using linear regression.

Some observations below, from a frequentist approach looking at only ‘p’ values produced from linear regression:

  • From the linear regression output below, variables oscar_season, summer_season, best_pic_win, best_dir_win, top200_box, best_actress_win, best_actor_win have the highest p values (>> .05), hence expect them to have relatively little impact on audience_scores
  • variables feature_film, drama, imdb_num_votes are also above >0.05, but marginally so and these may still be a factor in the overall linear model
  • variables runtime, thtr_rel_year, imdb_rating, critics_score, best_pic_nom have p <.05 and are definite candidates for further analysis in optimizing the model
  • the adjusted R square from linear regression is ~76%, meaning that 24% of the variance cannot be explained by the full model based on linear regression.

As a next step, for variables with ‘p’ slightly above 0.05, I have used Bayes inference to test the null hypothesis H_0: \(\mu\) = 0, so for example, test the null hypothesis Does audience score get impacted by feature_film = yes or no..

I have noted some observations from the Bays inference analysis below as an example.

  • for feature_film: Bayes Factor (BF) is significant in favor of the alternative hypothesis that \(\mu\) for audience score for (feature vs non feature) movies is statistically different
  • similarly for the variable drama, with BF at 22.65 we can draw a conclusion in favor of the alternate hypothesis, this was also evident from the pairs plot
bayes_inference(y=audience_score,x=feature_film,data=movies,statistic='mean',type='ht',alternative='twosided',null=0)

The modelling objective is to predict the popularity of a movie as indicated by audience_score and optimize it with the most optimum set of variables while not sacricifing too much on accuracy . We use function ‘stepAIC’ to optimize the lm model ‘lm_mod’ output produced earlier.

As default, the code below does a backward reduction using minimization of AIC scores as a criteria and arrives at a reduced set of influencor variables.

lm_optim <- stepAIC(lm_mod,trace=FALSE,k=2)
lm_optim$anova

This reduces the model to:

Model (reduced to 8 variables now):

audience_score ~ mpaa_rating_R + runtime + thtr_rel_year + imdb_rating + critics_score + best_pic_nom + best_actor_win + best_actress_win

while bringing down AIC from 3006.94 to 2998.80.

As a next step to validate my results from stepAIC above, I have also used bayesian linear regression model using the same initial predictor variables. BAS provides several algorithms to sample from posterior distribution models for use in BMA or model selection. MCMC is recommended where enumeration is not possible. Zellner-Siow Cauchy distribution is used to assign prior distribution for regression coefficients. A uniform distribution is used for the prior probabilities for all models.

# remove values with 'NA' in runtime variable
colSums(is.na(movies))

The output from the baysean linear regression model shows ‘P’, the probability of each variable’s importance on audience score. The variables: mpaa_rating_R (20.4%), runtime (46.6%),imdb_rating (99.9%),critics_score (87.9%) have the highest P values. This is inline with our earlier conclusion from stepAIC, but has shrunk the list of important variables down to 4.

Part 5: Prediction

I will use the final model to predict audience scores for the 2016 movie ’Passengers.

I start by creating a single data record for the movie with an audience_score of 63.

The code below creates a data frame taking the variable values from the 2 databases. We use the final model ‘final_basLM’ created with the optimized set of variables to predict audience_score and compare it to the actual audience score value taken from the database

passenger2016 <- data.frame(runtime=116, thtr_rel_year=2016, imdb_rating=7, imdb_num_votes=247748, critics_score=41,
                         audience_score=63, best_pic_nom='no',best_pic_win='no',best_actor_win='no',
                         best_actress_win='no',best_dir_win='no',top200_box='no',feature_film='yes',drama='yes',
                         mpaa_rating_R='no',oscar_season='yes',summer_season='no')


# Get the prediction
pass_predict <- predict(final_basLM, newdata=passenger2016, estimator="BMA", se.fit=TRUE)

df <- data.frame(m='Passenger', p=sprintf("%2.1f", pass_predict$Ybma), k=sprintf("%2.1f",passenger2016$audience_score))
colnames(df) <- c('Movie Title', 'Predicted audience score', 'Actual audience score')

print(df)
##   Movie Title Predicted audience score Actual audience score
## 1   Passenger                     68.3                  63.0

Part 6: Conclusion

The Baysean model provides satisfactory prediction results. As summary

  • I was able to reduce the explanatory variable set down to 3 from the original 32 + 5 newly added variables.
  • The model predicted audience rating for Passengers quite accurately as 68.5 vs actual rating of 63
  • The number of sampling’s done with the reduced set comes down significantly (about 30 from 6000+) when the final variable set is used, as expected

The Bayseaon model is richer in providing probabilities to help make better decisions on how to optimize. The analysis can further be improved by considering suitable treatment of outliers.
